Sometimes you find that once-in-a-lifetime horse. That special one has it all. The looks, the talent, and a special pedigree. Requiem J&F Champblanc is one of those horses. The beautifully coloured chestnut never fails to grab your attention in the arena. He has an easy confidence about him when working; light-footed, athletic, and very scopey is what comes to mind when you see him jump.

Requiem is a son of Quaprice Bois Margot (Quidam de Revel x Lord) who unfortunately died at a very young age. Quaprice was very successful with Julien Epaillard at the 1.60 level and sired many excellent horses like Viking d’la Rousserie, Ratina d’la Rousserie, Baltic VDL, Beau Goss du Park, Sangria de Coty and many more 1.60 horses. 

The mother of Requiem, Hanky Panky, is a daughter of the great Calvaro Z (Caletto I x Capitol I) who jumped for many years at the highest level with Jos Lansink and John Whitaker. He won the Dutch championships in 1997, a medal during the Europeans that same year, and also jumped some great rounds at the Olympics in Sydney. Besides that, he can still be found at the top of the WBFSH Sire Ranking. The oldest daughter of Hanky Panky is jumping internationally at the 1.30 level. In the direct damline we find two 1.60 horses; Fleurivan de Koekelberg and Barough C.R. and also the 1.40 horse, Gorki F. 

Further in Requiems pedigree we see Heartbreaker. A stallion who almost needs no introduction at all. Besides a fantastic career with Peter Geerink, he provided the world with amazing showjumpers like Halifax van het Kluizebos, Romanov II, Toulon, Actionbreakerand VDL Group Zidane. 

Requiem J&F Champblanc has a great character, is very nice to ride with a pleasant and well-balanced canter, and shows a lot of talent on the jump. He was approved by Zangersheide as a 3-year-old and jumped exceptionally well during the Belgium stallion competition. He is set to continue his career with American rider Hunter Holloway. The first foals of Requiem look impressive and show the same light-footed canter. All of these aspects combined make Requiem a very interesting stallion for your breeding program!

We’re Hiring!

Hunter Holloway and team are now hiring a full time Groom position! Our team travels to shows up to 8 months of the year with international shows and winters in Ocala. 

We are seeking qualified applicants who are hardworking, self motivated and willing to work independently as well in a team environment.

Candidates must have experience handling and working with horses as well as have a good understanding for caring and grooming show horses. Braiding experience is desired but not required. Must be available to travel or stay at one of our barns as needed.

* Competitive weekly salary
* Housing provided

Position is required but not limited to:

* Groom/tack horses
* Bathe horses
* Provide basic care to horses
* Clipping
* General upkeep and tiding of barn (at home and shows)

**this is NOT a riding position**

Email resume to: hunter@hunterholloway.com

Wow. What. A. Week…. Thank you to everyone for reaching out with your kind words and support over the past week. I’m at a little bit of a loss for words but sitting here so incredibly grateful. These are the goals we work so hard towards and aim for, then for them to become a reality is such a surreal feeling. 

I am beyond thankful to the team of people that stay working tirelessly behind the scenes, making weeks like this possible. Dylan Gamble, Luis Sabino, Stephany McConnell, Katie Williams, Clint Halvorsrod, Dr. Stephanie Gibson, Fred van Straaten, Jessica Farrington and of course my family for their endless and unwavering support. Thank you all!!

Now for a special thank you to the grey mare that continues to leave me in awe of her. She gives her all and tries her heart out every time we step into an arena together. Forever grateful to her and can’t wait to see what else we can accomplish together. Pepita you are one of a kind 💛💛💛

Now for a few of my favorite pictures from this week.

Hunter Holloway est l’une des quelques belles surprises de la finale de la Coupe du monde Longines d’Omaha. Après cinq parcours, l’Américaine de vingt-cinq ans a signé la meilleure performance de sa jeune carrière en accompagnant sur le podium deux cadors de la discipline, dont Henrik von Eckermann, numéro un mondial, double champion du monde et champion olympique par équipes. Un succès inenvisageable sans le génie de son attachante Pepita con Spita, qui lui donne mille et une raisons d’avoir le sourire jusqu’aux oreilles.
